Final Project¶

Final Project for the Summer Course of Python for Social Sciences given by QLAB. Our task was to graph and analyse a database provided by the lecturer. It is published as a html page at: https://estcab00.github.io/final-project-python-CCSS/

Authors:¶

  • Cabrera Bonilla, Esteban Simn (20190478) (esteban.cabrera@pucp.edu.pe)

  • Egusquiza Portillo, Luis Fernando (20193469) (egusquiza.l@pucp.edu.pe)

3. Transforming the file¶

We transform the database by consolidating multiple year columns into a single "Year" column using the melt function. The resulting DataFrame (df_melted) is then displayed to illustrate the initial rows of this transformed structure, facilitating analysis and visualization in an educational Jupyter notebook.

In [3]:
# First, we create a list of year columns
year_columns = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('19') or col.startswith('20')]

# Then, we perform the transformation using melt to reorganize the DataFrame
df_melted = df.melt(id_vars=['Country Name', 'Country Code', 'Series Name', 'Series Code'],
                    value_vars=year_columns,
                    var_name='Year',
                    value_name='Value')

# Convert the 'Year' column to a cleaner format (removing '[YR' and ']')
df_melted['Year'] = df_melted['Year'].str.extract('(\d{4})')

# Show the first few rows of the transformed DataFrame

Now, we select two indicators, 'CO2 emissions (metric tons per capita)' and 'GDP growth (annual %)', and identify five countries: 'United States', 'China', 'India', 'Germany', and 'Brazil'.

Subsequently, we filter a DataFrame (df_melted) to include only the rows related to these chosen indicators and countries. The 'Value' column undergoes conversion to numeric format, with any non-numeric values, like '..', being replaced by NaN. This processed DataFrame (filtered_df) is then ready for use in creating visualizations or conducting further analysis specifically focused on the specified indicators and countries.

In [4]:
# Selected indicators: 'CO2 emissions (metric tons per capita)' and 'GDP growth (annual %)'
indicator_1 = 'CO2 emissions (metric tons per capita)'
indicator_2 = 'GDP growth (annual %)'

# Selected countries: 'United States', 'China', 'India', 'Germany', 'Brazil'
example_countries = ['United States', 'China', 'India', 'Germany', 'Brazil']

# Filter the DataFrame for these indicators and countries
filtered_df = df_melted[(df_melted['Series Name'].isin([indicator_1, indicator_2])) &
                        (df_melted['Country Name'].isin(example_countries))]

# Convert the 'Value' column to numeric, replacing '..' with NaN
filtered_df['Value'] = pd.to_numeric(filtered_df['Value'], errors='coerce')

4. Graphs¶

First graph¶

In the first graph, we depict the evolution of CO2 emissions for selected countries over the years, utilizing seaborn for a clear visualization with custom labels, legend, and grid lines in an educational Jupyter notebook.

In [5]:
# Graph 1: Evolution of CO2 emissions for each selected country
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(data=filtered_df[filtered_df['Series Name'] == indicator_1],
             x='Year', y='Value', hue='Country Name')
plt.title('Evolution of CO2 Emissions by Country')
plt.ylabel('CO2 Emissions (Metric Tons per Capita)')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title='Country')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# We filter relevant rows and select necessary columns
df_filtered = df_China[df_China['Series Name'].isin(['CO2 emissions (metric tons per capita)', 'GDP growth (annual %)'])]

# We pivot the DataFrame to obtain desired columns
df_pivoted = df_filtered.pivot(index=['Country Name', 'Year'], columns='Series Name', values='Value').reset_index()

# We rename columns if necessary
df_pivoted.columns.name = None  # To remove column names after pivoting
df_pivoted.rename(columns={
    'CO2 emissions (metric tons per capita)': 'CO2_emissions',
    'GDP growth (annual %)': 'GDP_growth'
}, inplace=True)

# We convert columns 'Year', 'CO2_emissions', and 'GDP_growth' to numeric types
df_pivoted['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(df_pivoted['Year'], errors='coerce')
df_pivoted['CO2_emissions'] = pd.to_numeric(df_pivoted['CO2_emissions'], errors='coerce')
df_pivoted['GDP_growth'] = pd.to_numeric(df_pivoted['GDP_growth'], errors='coerce')

Now we define a function plot_time_series to create a time series plot on a given set of axes. It takes input parameters for x-axis values (x), y-axis values (y), color of the plot (color), and labels for the x-axis (xlabel) and y-axis (ylabel). The function uses the provided information to plot the time series, set axis labels, and adjust tick parameters on the y-axis to match the specified color. This function is designed for the final project of the QLAB Summer Python Course, as indicated in the docstring.

In [9]:
def plot_time_series(axes, x, y, color, xlabel, ylabel):
    ''' This function plots a time series, taking the axes, x-axis values, y-axis values, color, and axis labels. 
        It was designed for the final project of the QLAB Summer Python Course
    
        Inputs:
        
        axes: The axes being worked on
        x: Dates for the x-axis (usually the index)
        y: Values for the y-axis
        color: Color of the axes
        xlabel: Label for the x-axis
        ylabel: Label for the y-axis
    '''
    
    axes.plot(x, y, color=color)
    
    axes.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    
    axes.set_ylabel(ylabel, color=color)
    
    axes.tick_params(axis='y', colors=color)
In [10]:
plt.style.use('default')

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

plt.title('Carbon Emissions and GDP Growth in China')

plot_time_series(ax, df_pivoted.Year, df_pivoted.CO2_emissions, 
                        "darkblue", 'Time (years)', 'CO2 emissions (metric tons per capita)')

ax2 = ax.twinx()

plot_time_series(ax2, df_pivoted.Year, df_pivoted.GDP_growth, 
                        "darkgreen", 'Time (years)', 'GDP growth (annual %)')

fig.tight_layout(pad=1.0)

plt.show()

Forth graph¶

We transform the dataset by consolidating scattered year columns into a unified "Year" column. Then, we select two indicators, 'Access to electricity (% of population)' and 'Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)', filter and prepare the data accordingly. The datasets for each indicator are then merged based on country and year. Subsequently, a scatter plot is generated using seaborn, depicting the relationship between access to electricity and hospital beds per country. The plot is adorned with descriptive labels and grid lines for enhanced clarity in visualizing these indicators across different countries.

In [11]:
# We transform year columns into a single "Year" column
year_columns = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('19') or col.startswith('20')]
df_melted = df.melt(id_vars=['Country Name', 'Country Code', 'Series Name', 'Series Code'],
                    value_vars=year_columns,
                    var_name='Year',
                    value_name='Value')
df_melted['Year'] = df_melted['Year'].str.extract('(\d{4})')

# We select two indicators to analyze their relationship
indicator_1 = 'Access to electricity (% of population)'
indicator_2 = 'Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)'

# We filter and prepare the data
df_indicator_1 = df_melted[df_melted['Series Name'] == indicator_1]
df_indicator_2 = df_melted[df_melted['Series Name'] == indicator_2]
df_indicator_1['Value'] = pd.to_numeric(df_indicator_1['Value'], errors='coerce')
df_indicator_2['Value'] = pd.to_numeric(df_indicator_2['Value'], errors='coerce')
df_merged = pd.merge(df_indicator_1, df_indicator_2, on=['Country Name', 'Year'], suffixes=('_Electricity', '_Beds'))
